<p>When we think of exercise, we tend to focus on getting fitter by burning calories. Because of this, most people think that the only way we burn calories is through exercise.&nbsp;</p>



<p>But our bodies also burn calories when at rest. Whether we’re sitting on the couch or catching up on sleep, we burn different amounts of calories. Even when we lie doing nothing at all, our bodies require energy to sustain vital bodily functions.&nbsp;</p>



<p>We can call this metabolic process our <a href="https://link.springer.com/referenceworkentry/10.1007/978-3-319-47829-6_1429-1" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">basal metabolic rate</a>, or BMR. This accounts for the calories we burn to maintain breathing, pump blood, and cell maintenance or repair.&nbsp;</p>



<p>In our journey towards optimal health and better quality of life, understanding your BMR is essential. The BMR calculator provides on-demand feedback, giving instant access to the calories needed to maintain important functions.&nbsp;</p>



<p>In this article, we discuss how it works, the benefits of using it, and tips on how to boost metabolism.</p>



<div class="wp-block-group ft-snippet is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container">
<p class="has-medium-font-size">How To Use This BMR Calculator</p>



<p>The BMR calculator can be used correctly by following simple steps.&nbsp;</p>



<ul>
<li><strong>Start At The Input Page — </strong>&nbsp;Type in your weight, height, age, and sex using the respective fields shown.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Check The Input Page — </strong>Check that all information given is correct.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Start The Basal Metabolism Calculator Process — </strong>Click the <em>calculate</em> button underneath the information sections.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Examine The Output —</strong> The output page should display your basal metabolic rate, activity level, and total daily energy expenditure.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<p>The output information can be used to adjust energy intake according to your training style and goals.</p>
</div></div>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading list-start"><strong>How Does This BMR Calculator Work?</strong></h2>



<p>Let’s start by explaining how the BMR calculator works so you can get more familiar with the different components. We can split this into the input data and the output data.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Input data</strong></h3>



<p>To accurately calculate your BMR, you need to provide some basic details. These are:&nbsp;</p>



<ul>
<li><strong>Weight —</strong>&nbsp; Input your weight in kilograms or pounds.</li>



<li><strong>Height — </strong>Input your height in centimeters, inches, or feet.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Age — </strong>Input your current age in years.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Gender — </strong>Input your gender assigned at birth, either male or female.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Body Fat Percentage — </strong>Input your body fat percentage if you know it. This can give you a more precise calculation using the Katch-McArdke formula. If not, leave this section blank.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Output data</strong>&nbsp;</h3>



<p>Once you’ve given the data above, click <em>calculate</em> to get your output data. Your basal metabolic rate calculator will generate the following outputs:</p>



<ul>
<li><strong>Your Basal Metabolic Rate — </strong>This indicates the calories your body burns at rest without exercising.</li>



<li><strong>Your Activity Level — </strong>This gives your activity level based on an activity scale. Examples include sedentary, lightly active, moderately active, and very active. This is to determine how your activity level will impact your energy, or calorie needs.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Your Total Daily Energy Expenditure — </strong>This refers to the <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8370708/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">total calories your body burns</a> daily. This includes your BMR estimate and the amount you burn through physical activity.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<p>You may receive additional outputs depending on the metabolic rate calculator. These outputs may include:&nbsp;</p>



<ul>
<li>Metabolic age.</li>



<li>Metabolism optimization tips.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Weight loss goals breakdown.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>How Does This Tool Work?</strong></h3>



<p>This BMR computation tool uses the following formulas to provide output estimations. Each formula uses the different inputs provided to determine this.</p>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">BMR Formulas Used</h4>



<p><strong>Mifflin-St Jeor Equation:</strong></p>



<p>For men:</p>



<p>BMR = 10W + 6.25H &#8211; 5A + 5</p>



<p>For women:</p>



<p>BMR = 10W + 6.25H &#8211; 5A &#8211; 161</p>



<p><strong>Revised Harris-Benedict Equation:</strong></p>



<p>For men:</p>



<p>BMR = 13.397W + 4.799H &#8211; 5.677A + 88.362</p>



<p>For women:</p>



<p>BMR = 9.247W + 3.098H &#8211; 4.330A + 447.593</p>



<p><strong>Katch-McArdle Formula</strong>:</p>



<p>BMR = 370 + 21.6(1 &#8211; F)W</p>



<p>Where:</p>



<p>W is body weight in kg.</p>



<p>H is body height in cm.</p>



<p>A is age.</p>



<p>F is body fat in percentage.</p>



<p>The basal metabolic weight calculator uses the three established formulas above to estimate your basal metabolic rate. Each one has its strengths and weaknesses. These are some of them in more detail:</p>



<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9246861/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow"><strong>Katch-McArdle Formula</strong></a><strong> — </strong>This is primarily designed for those with higher body fat percentages, typically over 20%. It uses your body fat percentage as an additional input. This allows for a more accurate estimate of BMR, particularly for those with muscle mass outside of the normal ranges.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6068274/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow"><strong>Mifflin-St Jeor Equation</strong></a><strong> — </strong>Developed in 1990, this formula is considered the most accurate so it is the most widely used for general populations. It uses your weight, height, age, and gender to calculate your resting energy expenditure. While it’s generally accurate, it may give false readings for very muscular or overweight populations.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9967803/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow"><strong>Revised Harris-Benedict Equation</strong></a><strong> — </strong>Developed in 1984, this older formula offers a good alternative that’s still commonly used. It uses the same input variables as the Mifflin-St Jeor but with different coefficients. Because of this, its accuracy tends to vary between individuals.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<p>The BMR calculator mentioned mainly uses the Mifflin-St Jeor equation. However, the tool lets you choose between the formulas. This gives you more personalized results depending on your characteristics.</p>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">BMR Variables</h4>



<p>The calculator for metabolic rate uses the input information to generate the outputs. Therefore, the accuracy of the outputs depends on the accuracy of the inputs provided. <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31241289/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">Factors affecting your BMR</a> may include:</p>



<ul>
<li><strong>Your Weight —</strong> This is often the biggest influencing factor. People with larger body mass burn more <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/ejcn2014216" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">calories</a> to sustain basic bodily functions.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Your Height — </strong>This is another big influencing factor alongside weight. Taller people tend to have a higher BMR because of the increased organ size and larger muscle mass.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Your Age —</strong> As you age, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7600750/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">BMR tends to decrease</a>. This is due to changes in body composition and metabolic efficiency.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Your Gender — </strong>Men typically <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10443258/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">have higher BMRs</a> compared to women. This is mainly due to them having a larger muscle mass alongside hormonal differences.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Your Body Fat Percentage — </strong>When used with the Katch-McArdle formula, body fat percent changes the BMR estimate for those with higher body fat percentages.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>BMR Tests</strong></h4>



<p>The BMR calculator is easy to use and provides a convenient estimate. However, other <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30124219/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">BMR measurement methods</a> offer higher accuracy. This comes at the expense of convenience.&nbsp;</p>



<ul>
<li><strong>Direct Calorimetry — </strong>This is regarded as the gold standard method for estimating BMR. It requires you to stay in a controlled chamber environment for several hours. However, its high cost makes it inaccessible and impractical for most people.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<ul>
<li><strong>Indirect Calorimetry — </strong>This is also a good method of estimating BMR. It uses specialized equipment to measure your oxygen and carbon dioxide exchange to get your BMR. It&#8217;s more accessible than direct Calorimetry but still not widely available.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<p>Both of these tests are performed in specialized laboratories. Each process involves measuring your energy expenditure under controlled conditions. This provides a more accurate way to calculate BMR by eliminating the confounding variables.&nbsp;</p>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Resting Metabolic Rate</strong></h4>



<p><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4535334/#:~:text=Resting%20and%20basal%20metabolic%20rate,subject%20completely%20rested%20(27)." target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">BMR and resting metabolic rate</a>, or RMR, are often used interchangeably. They are closely related but are different measurements that should be seen as such. They represent the body’s minimum energy needs at rest but are not the same.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The resting metabolic rate is the minimum amount of energy needed to maintain essential functions when resting. While it sounds similar, BMR is measured in the morning following an overnight fast. Typically there would also be no exercise for 24 hours before.&nbsp;</p>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Modern Wisdom</strong></h4>



<p>Beyond simply estimating a BMR number, the calculator provides contemporary knowledge and insight. Because of this, it offers additional value. The additional knowledge and insights include:</p>



<ul>
<li><strong>Recommended Activity And Dietary Adjustments — </strong>The BMR calculator&#8217;s output can change your BMR into estimated calories based on your activity levels. With this, you can understand your energy requirements and make necessary adjustments according to your training goals.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Personalized Insights — </strong>Alongside the output shown, the BMR calculator may give relevant tips based on your BMR and activity level. This is often individualized according to your nutrition, fitness, and weight management.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Transparency — </strong>The BMR calculator operates with full transparency, showing information about the formulas used and their sources. This full transparency allows you to learn about the science behind the equations.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Scientific Backing — </strong>Each of the principles and formulas used is based on scientific research. Each one has been validated using scientific studies and clinical nutrition research.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<p>Note that although the BMR tool provides informed estimations, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4535334/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">individual variations may exist</a>. If you’re unsure or prefer more specialized testing options, consult a qualified healthcare professional. They can offer a more precise BMR measurement using the methods above.</p>



